.sh 1 "Procedures"
.lp
This \fI\)Load Grouping\fR extension provides for an additional level of
control over the traffic distribution patterns within an Application Server.
This extension provides the \fI\)Load Distribution\fR parameter which may be
optionally included in the \fB\)REG REQ\fR, \fB\)ASPAC\fR and \fB\)ASPAC
ACK\fR messages.  In addition, it supplements the ASP State Maintenance and
ASP Traffic Maintenance procedures.
.sh 2 "ASP State Maintenance"
.lp
In addition to the SGP mainting the state of each remote ASP in each
Application Server that the ASP is configured to receive traffic, under this
extension, the SGP \fB\)MAY\fR also maintain the state of each remote ASP in
each \fI\)Load Group\fR within an Application server that the ASP is
configured to receive traffic.  The \fI\)Load Group\fR state is maintained
separate from the ASP and AS states.
.sh 3 "Load Group State"
.lp
The state of the \fI\)Load Group\fR is maintained in the Signalling User
Adaptation Layer on the SGPs.  The state of the \fI\)Load Group\fR changes due
ASP state transitions.  The possible states of a \fI\)Load Group\fR are:
.ip "\fB\)LG-DOWN\fR:" 16
The \fI\)Load Group\fR is unavaialble.  This state implies that all related
ASPs are in the \fB\)ASP-DOWN\fR state for this \fI\)Load Group\fR.
Initially, the \fI\)Load Group\fR will be in this state.
.ip "\fB\)LG-INACTIVE\fR:" 16
The \fI\)Load Group\fR is available but no application traffic is active (i.e,
one or more related ASPs are in the \fB\)ASP-INACTIVE\fR state, but none are
in the \fB\)ASP-ACTIVE\fR state within the \fI\)Load Group\fR).
.ip "\fB\)LG-ACTIVE\fR:" 16
The \fI\)Load Group\fR is available and application traffic is active.  This
state implies that at least one ASP is in the \fB\)ASP-ACTIVE\fR state within
the \fI\)Load Group\fR.
.sh 3 "Application Server State"
.lp
Where ASPs are configured to operation within \fI\)Load Groups\fR under this
extension, the Application Server state is interpreted as provided in the
Signalling User Adaptation Layer specifications.
