.sh 2 "Notification"
.lp
When the SGP or IPSP notifies its UA peer with a NTFY messages which concerns
an ASP, it \fB\)MUST\fR include the \fI\)Load Group\fR (if available)
along with the ASP Identifier in the message.  The NTFY messages to which this
applies are:
.ip "\fI\)NTFY(""ASP Failure"") \-\fR"
When the SGP or IPSP notifies the active and inactive ASPs in an AS that it
has detected the failure of an ASP or the failure of an association to an ASP
(i.e. SCTP Communication Lost Indication), it \fB\)MUST\fR include the
\fI\)Load Group\fR (if available) with the ASP Identifier in the message.
When the Routing Context(s)/Interface Identifier(s) associated with the
Application Servers cannot be implied at the ASP from static configuration
data, the Routing Context/Interface Identifier(s) \fB\)MUST\fR also be placed
in the NTFY("ASP Failure") message.  The notifying SGP or IPSP \fB\)MAY\fR
also place the \fI\)Load Selection\fR parameter into the NTFY("ASP Failure")
message to indicate the traffic which was applicable to the load selection at
the time of the failure.

The purpose of this procedure is to inform the active and inactive ASPs, not
only of the ASP failure, but of the identity of the ASP and the load selection
for which the failed ASP was responsible.
.ip "\fI\)NTFY(""Alternate ASP Active in AS"") \-\fR"
When the SGP or IPSP notifies the previously active ASP in a override AS that
an alternate ASP has become active using the NTFY("Alternate ASP Active in
AS") message, it \fB\)MUST\fR include the \fI\)Load Group\fR (if
available) with the ASP Identifier in the message.
.lp
The purpose of this procedure is to inform the previously active ASP, not only
of the that another ASP has taken over the traffic for which the notified ASP
was previously responsible, but to also indicate the identify of the
overriding ASP and the load selection that was overridden.
